<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Quercus durata </i>is a slow-growing, evergreen shrub that grows to 3 m in height. Leaves are a dull dark green, convex, pubescent above, and densely hairy below. Shrubs produce large acorn crops at irregular intervals. Seeds germinate without stratification. Small mammals and jays cache acorns, which other wildlife also eat. Plants sprout from swollen root crowns and root suckers after damage to their trunks. Shrubs are shade tolerant. Other trees and shrubs act as nurse plants, moderating environmental conditions and offering seedlings and saplings protection (Nixon and Muller 1997). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Quercus durata </i>includes two subspecies. This alliance mainly involves var. <i>durata, </i>which grows on serpentine in the Coastal Ranges and foothills of the Sierra Nevada. The southern variety, var. <i>gabrielensis, </i> occupies barren gneiss-derived soils in the San Gabriel Mountains. Serpentine substrates are famous for rare species and endemics, including the following CNPS list 1B plants: <i>Arctostaphylos bakeri </i>ssp. <i>sublaevis, A. stanfordiana </i>ssp. <i>raichei, </i>and <i>Ceanothus ferrisiae</i>. <br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance have high fidelity to serpentine or other ultramafic substrates (Alexander et al. 2007, Kruckeberg 1984). Others (O’Geen et al. 2007, Rivas- Martinez 1997) refer to this alliance as the <i>“Quercetum duratae.” </i>It is typically dominant or co-dominant in mesic sites, including north-facing slopes. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
