    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Af-g, Aj-k). Stands occur in the Santa Lucia Mountains of Monterey and San Luis Obispo Cos. (Alexander et al. 2007). Small stands occur in the Santa Cruz Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-c, Ae, Ah). Stands are diverse and patchy, including those on Mount Diablo (Ertter and Bowerman 2002), Coyote Ridge (Evens and San 2004), on the eastern crest of the Red Mountain area in the Mount Hamilton Range (Sharsmith 1982), and south to Figueroa Mountain in Santa Barbara Co. (Alexander et al. 2007). Some stands in the Diablo Range occupy transition zones between sedimentary and serpentine substrates, and contain <i>Quercus wislizeni</i> or <i>Cercocarpus montanus</i> (Evens et al. 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ag, Al-m). Stands exist on Mount Tamalpais (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a, Evens and Kentner 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). Stands are common in the serpentine chaparral of Napa and Yolo Cos. Some stands occur on Franciscan formation and volcanic substrate in this section as at Hale Ridge RNA (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca). Stands are widespread on the North Coast ophiolite at Frenzel Creek RNA (Cheng 2004), at the McLaughlin Natural Reserve and surrounding areas (Harrison 1997, 1999), and in Napa Co. (Thorne et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fb). Stands are common near the Melones fault zone from Magalia in Butte Co. south to Eldorado Co. (Alexander et al. 2007). Several stands in the vicinity of Nevada City associate with stands of the <i>Hesperocyparis macnabiana</i> alliance and on more mesic settings and with others of the <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> and <i>Arctostaphylos viscida</i> alliances on more xeric sites and gabbroic soils (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Many <i>Quercus durata </i>stands have suffered from mining, clearing, or other development activities. <i>Ericameria nauseosa </i>colonizes disturbed sites easily, so managers used it in restoration projects. Because shrubs on serpentine are more fire sensitive and may recruit slowly, they may be especially susceptible to excessively frequent or poorly timed fires (Parker 1990a). </div>
</div>

    

    

